## Interpretation

### Plot 1 — Unemployment: SA vs Brazil
South Africa's unemployment rate has remained structurally high throughout the period, hovering around 25–35%, far above Brazil's rate which peaked during its 2015–2017 recession before recovering. This reflects deep-rooted issues in South Africa including skills mismatches, rigid labour markets, and weak economic growth following the global financial crisis and load-shedding era.

### Plot 2 — Inflation vs Prime Lending Rate (SA)
The South African Reserve Bank (SARB) operates under an inflation-targeting framework, with a target band of 3–6%. The chart shows that the prime lending rate broadly tracks inflation — rising when inflation spikes (e.g. 2002, 2008, 2022) and falling during low-inflation periods. This reflects the SARB's use of interest rate policy as the primary tool for managing price stability.
